=== 7.2 The Math

*Step 1 — Compute each head independently:*

For stem:[h = 1, \ldots, H]:

[stem]
++++
\begin{aligned}
Q^{h} &= X W_q^{h} \in \mathbb{R}^{T\times d_k} \\
K^{h} &= X W_k^{h} \in \mathbb{R}^{T\times d_k} \\
V^{h} &= X W_v^{h} \in \mathbb{R}^{T\times d_v} \\
\text{head}^{h} &= \operatorname{softmax}\!\left(\frac{Q^{h}{K^{h}}^{\top}}{\sqrt{d_k}} + M\right) V^{h}
\end{aligned}
++++

*Step 2 — Concatenate:*

[stem]
++++
\operatorname{MultiHead} = \operatorname{concat}(\text{head}^1, \text{head}^2, \ldots, \text{head}^{H})   \in \mathbb{R}^{T \times (H\cdot d_v)}
++++

Since stem:[d_v = d/H], the concatenated output has shape stem:[[T \times d\]] — the same as the input.

*Step 3 — Output projection:*

stem:[W_o \in \mathbb{R}^{d\times d}] is a learned output projection matrix.

[stem]
++++
\text{Output} = \operatorname{MultiHead} \cdot W_o \in \mathbb{R}^{T\times d}
++++

The final output projection mixes information across heads.

*Full formula:*

[stem]
++++
\text{MHA}(X) = [\text{head}^1 \| \text{head}^2 \| \ldots \| \text{head}^{H}]\, W_o
++++

where stem:[\text{head}^{h} = \operatorname{Attention}(X W_q^{h}, X W_k^{h}, X W_v^{h})].
